SUMMARY:2026 South Asian Studies Graduate Symposium
DESCRIPTION:The Dhar India Studies Program at Indiana University will hos
 t the South Asian Studies Graduate Student Symposium on Saturday\, April 
 25\, 2026\, at the Indiana Memorial Union. This daylong event brings toge
 ther graduate students from across disciplines to present research on Sou
 th Asia\, fostering conversation on topics ranging from urban environment
 s and social inequality to culture\, language\, and politics.  The sympos
 ium will feature a keynote address by Dr. Deepasri Baul (https://history.
 illinois.edu/directory/profile/deepasri) (University of Illinois\, Urbana
 -Champaign)\, titled "Sanctity of Property: Claims of Ownership over a Si
 kh Shrine in 1913 Delhi." Her work examines how religion\, law\, and urba
 n space intersect in colonial South Asia\, offering insight into broader 
 questions of authority\, ownership\, and conflict.  The program includes 
 paper panels\, lightning talks\, and opportunities for discussion through
 out the day\, followed by a reception. Below is the full schedule:&#160\;
   9:30 AM&#160\; &#160\; &#160\; &#160\;Arrival and Continental Breakfast
   10:00 AM&#160\; &#160\; Opening Remarks (Karen Stoll Farrell\, Director
  of Dhar India Studies)  10:15 - 11:30 Keynote Address and Q and A  Intro
 duction: Michael Dodson\, Department of HistoryPresenter: Professor Deepa
 sri Baul\, University of Illinois  &#160\;  11:30 - 1:00 LUNCH  1:00 - 2:
 15 Paper Panel: Interdisciplinary Approaches to Cities and the Environmen
 t in South Asia  Introduction: Purnima Bose\, Department of EnglishPresen
 ters: Diganta Mandal\, Ishita Sehgal\, and Brock DeMark  2:15 – 2:30 BR
 EAK  2:30 - 3:45 Lightning TalksPresenters: Annewsa Ghosh\, Gul E. Zahra\
 , Onyinyechukwu Chidi-Ogbolu\, and Yogesh Upadhyay  3:45 – 4:00 Closing
  Remarks (Rebecca Manring\, Dhar Program Director of Language Instruction
 )Reception to follow
