LOCATION:355 N. Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 1060
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Lucia Guerra Reyes
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Dr. Lucia Guerra Reyes as she presents Contextualizing Reproduct
 ive Aging in Peru: Medical Pluralism and the Midlife Transition.Abstract:
 The timing and experiences of reproductive aging\, the process culminatin
 g in the cessation of menstruation\, are often framed as universal\, yet 
 they vary significantly across ecological\, social\, and cultural context
 s. In this presentation\, I examine extant research on reproductive aging
  in Peru through the lens of medical pluralism\, situating menopause as a
  process rather than a discrete event within a broader life course shaped
  by environment\, inequality\, and multiple systems of knowledge and care
 . Drawing on public health and anthropological sources\, I discuss variat
 ion both in the process itself and in how women interpret and manage midl
 ife bodily changes across plural medical systems\, including biomedical s
 ervices\, Indigenous knowledge frameworks\, and informal social networks.
  These plural pathways shape how symptoms are recognized\, whether care i
 s sought\, and how menopause is understood.  &#160\;Lucia Guerra-Reyes is
  an associate professor in applied health science. She is a medical anthr
 opologist and interdisciplinary researcher. Guerra-Reyes investigates the
  complexities of access to sexual and reproductive health and care for ma
 rginalized communities. She is interested in understanding how national p
 olicies of culturally appropriate care are enacted at the local level\; h
 ow health care providers view their role in extending care to under-serve
 d communities\; and how women make decisions about their reproductive liv
 es.&#160\;  &#160\;  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from 
 February through April\, with faculty and guest speakers engaging Latin A
 merica and the Caribbean through research on history\, culture\, language
 \, politics\, and the arts. Check the CLACS Calendar (https://events.iu.e
 du/clacs/) for details.
