BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School
DTSTART:20260512T160000Z
DTEND:20260512T170000Z
LOCATION:Teams Webinar &amp\; The Regenstrief Institute
GEO:39.779628;-86.180457
SUMMARY:Global Health Research Speaker Series - Dr. Tesfaye Mersha
DESCRIPTION:Join the IU Center for Global Health and the Regenstrief Inst
 itute's Center for Health Services Research for this quarter's Global Hea
 lth Research Speaker Series session featuring&#160\;Tesfaye (Tes) Mersha\
 , MS\, PhD (https://medicine.iu.edu/faculty/70187/mersha-tesfaye)  Direct
 or\, Precision Pulmonary Medicine Research Program and James A. Caplin Pr
 ofessor of Pulmonary Research at Indiana University School of Medicine  D
 r. Mersha's session is titled "Harnessing the Mobility of Minds to Addres
 s Development Challenges in Africa." Africa faces complex challenges in h
 ealth\, education\, and innovation that require collaborative solutions. 
 The Alliance for Research\, Innovation and Education (AfRIE) mobilize glo
 bal expertise to strengthen African universities and research centers thr
 ough virtual education\, mentorship\, and collaborative projects. This pr
 esentation will highlight the critical need for strategic human capital d
 evelopment and institution‑level capacity building to strengthen Public
  Health Genomics (PHG)\, using the "mobility of minds" within the African
  diaspora as a model. This approach implements virtual teaching\, mentors
 hip\, collaborative research\, and innovation ecosystems connecting local
  and diaspora scientists. Addressing these gaps is essential to advancing
  equitable healthcare and ensuring that genomic discoveries benefit Afric
 an populations.  Dr. Mersha's career in genetics and research began with 
 an interest in understanding the interplay between biology and the enviro
 nmental conditions that contribute to disease. Over time\, he has broaden
 ed his research interests to include genomics\, genetic ancestry\, racial
  disparities\, personalized medicine and bioinformatics. One of Dr. Mersh
 a's areas of expertise is multi-omics (genomics\, epigenomics\, transcrip
 tomics\, microbiome\, proteomics and metabolomics). For more than 10 year
 s\, he has worked to integrate multi-omics with statistical genetics and 
 bioinformatics methods to uncover the molecular architecture of medical c
 onditions\, such as asthma and asthma-related allergic diseases. Dr. Mers
 ha's lab performs a variety of computational and applied data analysis pr
 ojects\, including the development of statistical and genome informatics 
 tools that enable multiethnic admixture\, genome-wide association and omi
 cs integration studies of biomedical traits. The goal is to develop an in
 -depth understanding of the intricate interactions between genomic variat
 ions and environmental exposure in the etiology of complex diseases — a
 nd then translate these findings into clinical practice through collabora
 tions with clinicians.  This session is being held both virtually (via Te
 ams webinar) and in-person. If you plan to attend the session in-person a
 t the Regenstrief Institute you must register by Thursday\, May 7th at 10
  am Eastern Time and indicate this choice when you register. &#160\;  Add
 itionally\, please take note of the following in-person details:In-Person
  Location: Regenstrief Institute (Room 209/210)\, 1101 W. 10th Street\, I
 ndianapolis (corner of 10th Street and Wilson Street)  Parking: Public (f
 or fee) parking is available in the Wilson Street Garage which is adjacen
 t to the building.  Building Security: Regenstrief maintains a secure bui
 lding entrance. Event support from the Center for Global Health and the C
 enter for Health Services Research will be onsite to assist with entry an
 d other event logistics.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Join the IU Center for Global Health an
 d the Regenstrief Institute's Center for Health Services Research for thi
 s quarter's Global Health Research Speaker Series session featuring&#160\
 ;</p><p><a href="https://medicine.iu.edu/faculty/70187/mersha-tesfaye">Te
 sfaye (Tes) Mersha\, MS\, PhD</a></p><p>  Director\, Precision Pulmonary 
 Medicine Research Program and James A. Caplin Professor of Pulmonary Rese
 arch at Indiana University School of Medicine</p><p>  Dr. Mersha's sessio
 n is titled "<strong>Harnessing the Mobility of Minds to Address Developm
 ent Challenges in Africa.</strong>" Africa faces complex challenges in he
 alth\, education\, and innovation that require collaborative solutions. T
 he Alliance for Research\, Innovation and Education (AfRIE) mobilize glob
 al expertise to strengthen African universities and research centers thro
 ugh virtual education\, mentorship\, and collaborative projects. This pre
 sentation will highlight the critical need for strategic human capital de
 velopment and institution‑level capacity building to strengthen Public 
 Health Genomics (PHG)\, using the "mobility of minds" within the African 
 diaspora as a model. This approach implements virtual teaching\, mentorsh
 ip\, collaborative research\, and innovation ecosystems connecting local 
 and diaspora scientists. Addressing these gaps is essential to advancing 
 equitable healthcare and ensuring that genomic discoveries benefit Africa
 n populations.</p><p>  Dr. Mersha's career in genetics and research began
  with an interest in understanding the interplay between biology and the 
 environmental conditions that contribute to disease. Over time\, he has b
 roadened his research interests to include genomics\, genetic ancestry\, 
 racial disparities\, personalized medicine and bioinformatics. One of Dr.
  Mersha's areas of expertise is multi-omics (genomics\, epigenomics\, tra
 nscriptomics\, microbiome\, proteomics and metabolomics). For more than 1
 0 years\, he has worked to integrate multi-omics with statistical genetic
 s and bioinformatics methods to uncover the molecular architecture of med
 ical conditions\, such as asthma and asthma-related allergic diseases. Dr
 . Mersha's lab performs a variety of computational and applied data analy
 sis projects\, including the development of statistical and genome inform
 atics tools that enable multiethnic admixture\, genome-wide association a
 nd omics integration studies of biomedical traits. The goal is to develop
  an in-depth understanding of the intricate interactions between genomic 
 variations and environmental exposure in the etiology of complex diseases
  — and then translate these findings into clinical practice through col
 laborations with clinicians.</p><p>  This session is being held both virt
 ually (via Teams webinar) and in-person. If you plan to attend the sessio
 n in-person at the Regenstrief Institute you must register by Thursday\, 
 May 7th at 10 am Eastern Time and indicate this choice when you register.
  &#160\;</p><p>  Additionally\, please take note of the following in-pers
 on details:</p><ul><li>In-Person Location: Regenstrief Institute (Room 20
 9/210)\, 1101 W. 10th Street\, Indianapolis (corner of 10th Street and Wi
 lson Street)  </li><li>Parking: Public (for fee) parking is available in 
 the Wilson Street Garage which is adjacent to the building.  </li><li>Bui
 lding Security: Regenstrief maintains a secure building entrance. Event s
 upport from the Center for Global Health and the Center for Health Servic
 es Research will be onsite to assist with entry and other event logistics
 .  </li></ul>
